density electrical power sources and energy storage to be flight certified for high rate pulsed power, el$$, $$7827cd0fc3742a2a6d155500383934ec21afb8817d10e3d25cd50ebc6ecefd51$$, $${"A": "5ea3fb85c8d84e106a0fdc5f2d122545d2d0ec2bfd381341cec49a353150749e", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "14b38c2f203baa70fe378731034444d7409be9ab03a7549831a50cd7f3a4eaff"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/Army/RDTE - Vol 1 - Budget Activity 2.pdf$$, 289, $$2026-05-10T04:01:21.372876+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604245M$$, 2027, $$This line item funds improvements to the UH-1Y Venom and AH-1Z Viper aircraft and related systems, collectively referred to as H-1 aircraft.

H-1's belongs to the same unit, Marine Light Attack Helicopter Squadrons (HMLA), and are often flown together for complementary mission roles. The mission of the
HMLA is to support the combatant commander by providing offensive air support, utility support, armed escort, and airborne supporting arms coordination day or night
under all weather conditions during expeditionary, joint or combined operations. H-1s are capable of offensive air support (to include Counter Unmanned Aerial System
(CUAS) and Counter Maritime), armed escort, armed/visual reconnaissance, and airborne supporting arms coordination. The UH-1Y utility helicopter is further capable
of conducting combat assault transport, airborne command and control, casualty evacuation and special operations support. The UH-1Y is crewed by two pilots and
two crew chiefs with maximum capacity of 12 personnel. The AH-1Z attack helicopter is the Marine Corps primary provider of air to surface fire's capable of providing
volume of fires support for anti-armor, counter maritime, precision strike, CUAS, and anti-helicopter and point air defense via current armament including the Sidewinder
and Hellfire missiles, Joint Air-to-Ground Missile (JAGM), Advanced Precision Kill Weapon System (APKWS), Precision Attack Strike Munition (PASM), a chin-mounted
20mm turret, and a wide variety of forward-firing and external stores. The AH-1Z is a tandem, two-seat attack helicopter crewed by two pilots.

H-1's are fully delivered and are expected to fly into the 2050's as a replacement platform is developed and selected. The Marine Corps prioritized and invested in a H-1
Mid-Life Modernization strategy to cover fires gaps and bridge to an eventual replacement program. RDTE funding is a culmination of the planned mid-life modernization
strategy and aligning with the Marine Corps' top three H-1 priorities of lethality, Digital Interoperability (DI), and improved survivability, while enabling future capability
improvements. Funding for improvements align with the Marine Corps' top three H-1 priorities of lethality, Digital Interoperability (DI), and improved survivability, while
enabling future capability improvements. Development programs seek to improve readiness, increase aircraft availability, and decrease operating costs. Reliability
improvements and obsolescence management will reduce flight hour costs, maintain/increase operational capability, and increase time on wing. Improvements include
software upgrades and integration of test assets to support engineering development and testing to address hazard reports against air vehicle and engine, sensors and
weapons, and avionics components, systems, and subsystems, training, and aircrew systems as well as integration and testing related to the aircraft platforms.

This program is funded under SYSTEM DEVELOPMENT AND DEMONSTRATION because it includes those projects that have passed Milestone B approval and are
conducting engineering and manufacturing development tasks aimed at meeting validated requirements prior to full-rate production decision.
Development & Demonstration (SDD)$$, $$The H-1 Improvements program is designed to advance the entire H-1 fleet, which includes the AH-1Z Viper and UH-1Y Venom helicopters. This initiative aligns with the
Marine Corps' H-1 modernization strategy, emphasizing the integration of enhanced capabilities to increase the fleet's lethality, digital interoperability, and survivability.
Each upgrade is accompanied by dedicated Software Configuration Set (SCS) development, robust cybersecurity protocols, and thorough testing to address hazard
reports and maintain platform integrity.

Air Vehicle and Engine Improvements are a central focus of the modernization initiative, aiming to maintain the structural integrity and reliability of the H-1 fleet well
into the 2050s. Research, Development, Test, and Evaluation (RDT&E) funds are being allocated to analyze structural data, establish Damage Limits and Tolerances,
and ultimately reduce life cycle costs and maintenance demands. The Air Vehicle scope also includes enhancements to rotors, flight controls, drive systems, and the
development and testing of key airframe components such as the tail boom and fuselage. These efforts are designed to minimize wear, boost reliability, and address
any design or safety shortcomings. Development of auxiliary fuel cells increases operational range and endurance. The program also encompasses Rotorcraft Station
Control Unit (RSCU) software upgrades, thorough testing, and strengthened cybersecurity measures for the RSCU.

Avionics modernization is a key driver in elevating the Marine Corps H-1 fleet's capabilities, with particular emphasis on Digital Interoperability (DI), integrated avionics,
and improved situational awareness to enhance pilot and aircrew safety. The DI Integration initiative comprises a suite of systems designed to enable the H-1 platform
to function as both a kill web enabler and effector. This effort incorporates technologies such as Link-16, the Advanced Net-Enabled Weapons (ANEW) datalink, and the
Advanced Data Transfer System (ADTS). Upgrades include Degraded Visual Environment (DVE) systems, state-of-the-art cockpit displays, and a Health and Usage
Monitoring System (HUMS) to increase operational safety and reliability. Communications modernization efforts focus on enhanced COMSEC and Embedded Global
Positioning System (EGI) capabilities, along with the integration of a new Radar Altimeter (RADALT). Mandated systems such as the Automatic Dependent Surveillance-
Broadcast (ADS-B) and a Crash Survivable Flight Incident Recorder are also being incorporated to meet regulatory requirements. Additionally, the integration of the
Mobile User Objective System (MUOS) ensures continued satellite communication capability for the H-1 fleet. The program further encompasses the integration and
testing of Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) satellite communications, including Proliferated Low Earth Orbit (pLEO) systems, to strengthen command and control functions.

Sensors and weapons testing and integration are vital for maintaining a decisive combat advantage. The H-1 modernization plan prioritizes the development and
integration of advanced sensors and weapon systems to streamline the kill chain and enhance intelligence sharing across the battlefield. The following upgrades
for sensors, weapons, and Aircraft Survivability Equipment (ASE) directly support these modernization objectives. These enhancements are intended to counter
emerging threats, address system obsolescence, improve reliability, and offer substantial growth potential for future capabilities. Upgrades to sensors and Helmet-
Mounted Displays (HMDs) significantly boost situational awareness and targeting capabilities. The modernization plan features extensive software and hardware
improvements, ensuring that sensor data is efficiently fused into actionable intelligence for the aircrew. The AN/AAQ-30 Target Sight System (TSS) is tracking to receive
obsolescence upgrades, such as enhanced cameras and new software-driven features like expanded fields of view and auto-focus, all aimed at increasing the reliability
and performance of the fleet's primary targeting sensor. The Optimized TopOwl (OTO) HMD is being upgraded to improve reliability, boost readiness, and reduce the

 high repair costs currently associated with HMD components, ensuring pilots have continuous access to essential flight and targeting data. Additionally, the BRITE Star
 Block II system will undergo Target Location Error correction, resulting in improved accuracy for locating and designating targets.

A key priority of the modernization plan is to ensure H-1 can persist in contested environments. This involves integrating a suite of advanced ASE to detect and defeat
modern anti-aircraft threats. AN/APR-39D(V)2 advanced radar warning receiver provides improved threat detection, identification, and reporting accuracy, enhancing the
crew's situational awareness of radar-guided threats.

The integration of Distributed Aperture Infrared Countermeasures (DAIRCM) provides protection against infrared-guided missiles. This system is a top-level survivability
priority for the H-1 fleet. AN/ALE-47 & Square Expendables provides future integration of legacy weapons and emerging weapons. This ensures compatibility with
advanced decoys being developed for other platforms and increases the aircraft's defensive capacity. To serve as a kill web contributor, the H-1 is being equipped with
a diverse portfolio of kinetic and non-kinetic weapons. Joint Air-to-Ground Missile (JAGM) AGM-179 provides a "fire-and-forget" capability that significantly enhances
lethality and survivability. Future software upgrades will improve its effectiveness against Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS). Advanced Precision Kill Weapon System
(APKWS) upgrades continue for this reliable precision-guided rocket, including the certification of a proximity fuse to better engage UAS threats.

Development and integration of long-range precision fires like the Precision Attack Strike Munition (PASM), also known as the Long-Range Attack Missile (LRAM), are a
top lethality priority to enable H-1 to strike targets from a greater stand-off distance. Integration of the Sidewinder AIM-9X provides a critical air-to-air and anti-helicopter
capability. Includes integration of AN/ALQ-231 Intrepid Tiger II (IT-II), Electronic Warfare (EW) pod adds a non-kinetic effects capability, allowing H-1 to disrupt and
deny enemy systems. Improvements to the M299 and the integration of a Digital Rocket Launcher (DRL) are necessary to support these advanced munitions. These
upgrades are designed to improve the accuracy, range, and overall lethality of the platform against ground, air, and maritime targets.

These coordinated improvements will provide considerable growth potential for future weapon systems, launched effects, sensing systems, air vehicle improvements,
software improvements, and avionics upgrades, which will significantly increase mission effectiveness and survivability, while potentially reducing life cycle costs.
The efforts will also include integration of onboard mission planning, communications, digital fire control, self-navigation, night navigation/targeting, precision guided
munitions, and air-launched intercept missile weapon systems management in nearly identical crew stations, which significantly reduces training requirements. These
upgrades maximize commonality between all H-1 aircraft and provide needed improvements in crew and passenger reliability, survivability, payload, power available,
endurance, range, airspeed, maneuverability and supportability.

