A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
This line item funds improvements to the UH-1Y Venom and AH-1Z Viper aircraft and related systems, collectively referred to as H-1 aircraft.

H-1's belongs to the same unit, Marine Light Attack Helicopter Squadrons (HMLA), and are often flown together for complementary mission roles. The mission of the
HMLA is to support the combatant commander by providing offensive air support, utility support, armed escort, and airborne supporting arms coordination day or night
under all weather conditions during expeditionary, joint or combined operations. H-1s are capable of offensive air support (to include Counter Unmanned Aerial System
(CUAS) and Counter Maritime), armed escort, armed/visual reconnaissance, and airborne supporting arms coordination. The UH-1Y utility helicopter is further capable
of conducting combat assault transport, airborne command and control, casualty evacuation and special operations support. The UH-1Y is crewed by two pilots and
two crew chiefs with maximum capacity of 12 personnel. The AH-1Z attack helicopter is the Marine Corps primary provider of air to surface fire's capable of providing
volume of fires support for anti-armor, counter maritime, precision strike, CUAS, and anti-helicopter and point air defense via current armament including the Sidewinder
and Hellfire missiles, Joint Air-to-Ground Missile (JAGM), Advanced Precision Kill Weapon System (APKWS), Precision Attack Strike Munition (PASM), a chin-mounted
20mm turret, and a wide variety of forward-firing and external stores. The AH-1Z is a tandem, two-seat attack helicopter crewed by two pilots.

H-1's are fully delivered and are expected to fly into the 2050's as a replacement platform is developed and selected. The Marine Corps prioritized and invested in a H-1
Mid-Life Modernization strategy to cover fires gaps and bridge to an eventual replacement program. RDTE funding is a culmination of the planned mid-life modernization
strategy and aligning with the Marine Corps' top three H-1 priorities of lethality, Digital Interoperability (DI), and improved survivability, while enabling future capability
improvements. Funding for improvements align with the Marine Corps' top three H-1 priorities of lethality, Digital Interoperability (DI), and improved survivability, while
enabling future capability improvements. Development programs seek to improve readiness, increase aircraft availability, and decrease operating costs. Reliability
improvements and obsolescence management will reduce flight hour costs, maintain/increase operational capability, and increase time on wing. Improvements include
software upgrades and integration of test assets to support engineering development and testing to address hazard reports against air vehicle and engine, sensors and
weapons, and avionics components, systems, and subsystems, training, and aircrew systems as well as integration and testing related to the aircraft platforms.

This program is funded under SYSTEM DEVELOPMENT AND DEMONSTRATION because it includes those projects that have passed Milestone B approval and are
conducting engineering and manufacturing development tasks aimed at meeting validated requirements prior to full-rate production decision.




